ATP Webscrapping and Sentiment Analysis¶

Purpose¶

The objective of the notebook os to scrape data from the web about top tennis players, then pull their related tweets from twitter in order to do a sentiment analysis (polarity) and compare them. WIP.

Methodology¶

In order to do so, we will use the basic python librairies (pandas, numby, etc..) and myBeautifulSoup. We will scrape the data from wikipedia. The sentiment analysis will be done using NLP, NLTK and textblob. The first visualization will be done using matplotlib. The second visualization will be done using streamlit in order to have a full data applications (WIP). This notebook is for a personal use.

Results¶

The analysis resulted in a plot of the rolling moving averages of the sentiment analysis of the top 5 players of the time (according to wikipedia).

Suggested next steps¶

  • debug why all players have very similar results
  • adding other hashtag for the players regarding combinations of their first name, last name, nickname
  • finding ways to pull tweets where only one player is mentionned
  • adding multilingual treatment of the tweets with other NLP librairies (polyglot for example). For now we only pull english tweets, and use english NLP librairies.
  • visualising using streamlit to beautify and make it easier to access (put all the code into one .py file to use streamlit

Data import¶

We retrieve all the required data for the analysis. At the end, we split the dataset in a train and test set to avoid data snooping;

   <h1 class="firstHeading" id="firstHeading" lang="en">
    ATP Rankings
   </h1>
   <div class="mw-body-content" id="bodyContent">
    <div class="noprint" id="siteSub">
     From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
    </div>
    <div id="contentSub">
    </div>
    <div id="contentSub2">
    </div>

    </div>

    <div class="mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr" id="mw-content-text" lang="en">
     <div class="mw-parser-output">
      <p>
       The
       <b>
        ATP Rankings
       </b>
       are the merit-based method used by the
       <a href="/wiki/Association_of_Tennis_Professionals" title="Association of Tennis Professionals">
        Association of Tennis Professionals
       </a>
       (ATP) for determining the qualification for entry as well as the seeding of players in all singles and doubles tournaments.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ATP_rulebook_1-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-ATP_rulebook-1">
         [1]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The first rankings for singles were published on 23 August 1973 while the doubles players were ranked for the first time on 1 March 1976. Ranking points are awarded according to the stage of tournament reached, and the prestige of the tournament, with the four
       <a href="/wiki/Grand_Slam_(tennis)" title="Grand Slam (tennis)">
        Grand Slam tournaments
       </a>
       awarding the most points. The rankings are updated every Monday, and points are dropped 52 weeks after being awarded (with the exception of the
       <a href="/wiki/ATP_Finals" title="ATP Finals">
        ATP Finals
       </a>
       , from which points are dropped on the Monday following the last ATP Tour event of the following year).
       <a href="/wiki/Novak_Djokovic" title="Novak Djokovic">
        Novak Djokovic
       </a>
       is the current world No.1.
      </p>
      <div aria-labelledby="mw-toc-heading" class="toc" id="toc" role="navigation">

      <h2>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="History">
        History
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=ATP_Rankings&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: History">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h2>
      <p>
       The ATP began as the men's
       <a href="/wiki/Trade_union" title="Trade union">
        trade union
       </a>
       in 1972, through the combined efforts of
       <a href="/wiki/Jack_Kramer" title="Jack Kramer">
        Jack Kramer
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Cliff_Drysdale" title="Cliff Drysdale">
        Cliff Drysdale
       </a>
       , and
       <a href="/wiki/Donald_Dell" title="Donald Dell">
        Donald Dell
       </a>
       , and rose to prominence when 81 of its members boycotted the
       <a href="/wiki/1973_Wimbledon_Championships" title="1973 Wimbledon Championships">
        1973 Wimbledon Championships
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-2">
        <a href="#cite_note-2">
         [2]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Just two months later, in August, the ATP introduced its ranking system intended to objectify tournament entry criteria, which up to that point was controlled by national federations and tournament directors.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ATP_hist_pt1_3-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-ATP_hist_pt1-3">
         [3]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       The ATP's new ranking system was quickly adopted by men's tennis.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ATP_hist_pt2_4-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-ATP_hist_pt2-4">
         [4]
        </a>
       </sup>
       While virtually all ATP members were in favor of objectifying event participation, the system's first No. 1,
       <a href="/wiki/Ilie_N%C4%83stase" title="Ilie Năstase">
        Ilie Năstase
       </a>
       , lamented that "everyone had a number hanging over them," fostering a more competitive and less collegial atmosphere among the players.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-5">
        <a href="#cite_note-5">
         [5]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       The original ATP ranking criteria, which was then regularly published weekly only from mid-1979 and persisted through the 1980s, was based on averaging each player's results, though the details were revised a number of times.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ATP_hist_pt1_3-1">
        <a href="#cite_note-ATP_hist_pt1-3">
         [3]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ATP_hist_pt2_4-1">
        <a href="#cite_note-ATP_hist_pt2-4">
         [4]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Starting in 1990, in conjunction with the expansion of ATP purview as the new men's tour operator, the ranking criteria was replaced with a 'best of' system modeled after competitive downhill skiing.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ATP_hist_pt2_4-2">
        <a href="#cite_note-ATP_hist_pt2-4">
         [4]
        </a>
       </sup>
       This 'best of' system originally used 14 events but expanded to 18 in 2000.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ATP_hist_pt2_4-3">
        <a href="#cite_note-ATP_hist_pt2-4">
         [4]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <h2>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Overview">
        Overview
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=ATP_Rankings&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Overview">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h2>
      <p>
       A player's ATP Ranking is based on the total points he accrued in the following 19 tournaments (18 if he did not qualify for the ATP Finals):
      </p>
      <ul>
       <li>
        The four
        <a href="/wiki/Grand_Slam_(tennis)" title="Grand Slam (tennis)">
         Grand Slam
        </a>
        tournaments
       </li>
       <li>
        The eight mandatory
        <a href="/wiki/ATP_Tour_Masters_1000" title="ATP Tour Masters 1000">
         ATP Tour Masters 1000
        </a>
        tournaments,
        <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-6">
         <a href="#cite_note-6">
          [a]
         </a>
        </sup>
       </li>
       <li>
        The previous ATP Finals count until the Monday following the final regular-season ATP event of the following year.
        <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-7">
         <a href="#cite_note-7">
          [6]
         </a>
        </sup>
       </li>
       <li>
        The best six results from the non-mandatory ATP Tour 1000, all
        <a href="/wiki/ATP_Tour_500" title="ATP Tour 500">
         ATP Tour 500
        </a>
        ,
        <a href="/wiki/ATP_Tour_250" title="ATP Tour 250">
         ATP Tour 250
        </a>
        ,
        <a href="/wiki/ATP_Challenger_Tour" title="ATP Challenger Tour">
         ATP Challenger Tour
        </a>
        ,
        <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Futures_tournament" title="Futures tournament">
         Futures Series
        </a>
        and
        <a href="/wiki/Davis_Cup" title="Davis Cup">
         Davis Cup
        </a>
        tournaments played in the calendar year
        <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-8">
         <a href="#cite_note-8">
          [b]
         </a>
        </sup>
       </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
       For a better result within the same tour type to be transposed one has to wait for the expiry of the first worse result from previous year. It only expires at the drop date of that tournament and only if the player reached a worse result or has not entered the current year.
      </p>
      <p>
       Ranking points gained in a tournament are dropped 52 weeks later, with the exception of the
       <a href="/wiki/ATP_Finals" title="ATP Finals">
        ATP Finals
       </a>
       , from which points are dropped on the Monday following the last ATP Tour event of the following year.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ATP_rulebook_1-1">
        <a href="#cite_note-ATP_rulebook-1">
         [1]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       The
       <a href="/wiki/Monte-Carlo_Masters" title="Monte-Carlo Masters">
        Monte-Carlo Masters
       </a>
       1000 became optional in 2009, but if a player chooses to participate in it, its result is counted and his fourth-best result in an ATP 500 event is ignored (his three best ATP 500 results remain). From 2009 until 2015, if a player did not play enough ATP 500 events and did not have an ATP 250 or Challenger appearance with a better result, the Davis Cup was counted in the 500's table.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-DC_9-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-DC-9">
         [7]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The
       <a href="/wiki/World_Team_Cup" title="World Team Cup">
        World Team Cup
       </a>
       was also included before its cancellation in 2012.
      </p>
      <p>
       For the Davis Cup, from 2009 until 2015, points were distributed for the World Group countries. Instead of having an exact drop date they were gradually updated at each phase of the competition, comparing the player's results with his results from the previous year. E.g. if a player played two matches in a semifinal but plays one the next year only that one missing match will be extracted from his points).
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-DC_9-1">
        <a href="#cite_note-DC-9">
         [7]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       A player who is out of competition for 30 or more days, due to a verified injury, will not receive any penalty. The ATP Finals will count as an additional 19th tournament in the ranking of its eight qualifiers at season's end.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-10">
        <a href="#cite_note-10">
         [8]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       For every Grand Slam tournament or mandatory ATP Tour Masters 1000 tournament for which a player is not in the main draw, and was not (and, in the case of a Grand Slam tournament, would not have been, had he and all other players entered) a main draw direct acceptance on the original acceptance list, and never became a main draw direct acceptance, the number of his results from all other eligible tournaments in the ranking period that count for his ranking is increased by one.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ATP_rulebook_1-2">
        <a href="#cite_note-ATP_rulebook-1">
         [1]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       Once a player is accepted in the main draw of a Grand Slam tournament or ATP Tour Masters 1000 tournament,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-11">
        <a href="#cite_note-11">
         [c]
        </a>
       </sup>
       his result in this tournament counts for his ranking, regardless of whether he participates. A player's withdrawal from an ATP Tour 500 event, regardless of whether the withdrawal was on time, results in a zero point included as one of his best of four results. Further non-consecutive withdrawals results in a zero point allocation replacing the next best positive result for each additional withdrawal.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ATP_rulebook_1-3">
        <a href="#cite_note-ATP_rulebook-1">
         [1]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       Players with multiple consecutive withdrawals who are out of competition for 30 days or longer because of injury are not subject to a ranking penalty as long as verified and approved medical forms are provided; or, a player will not have the ranking penalty imposed if he completes the Promotional Activities requirement as specified under "Repeal of Withdrawal Fines and/or Penalties" or if the on-site withdrawal procedures apply.  Players may also appeal withdrawal penalties to a Tribunal who will determine whether the penalties are affirmed or set aside.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ATP_rulebook_1-4">
        <a href="#cite_note-ATP_rulebook-1">
         [1]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       Between 2000 and 2012, ranking points were awarded based on results in the Summer Olympics. This was changed before the 2016 Olympics where no ranking points were awarded.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-12">
        <a href="#cite_note-12">
         [9]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       With these rules, a player playing and winning the mandatory 4 Grand Slams and 8 ATP Masters 1000 events, a further 5 ATP 500 events and the
       <a href="/wiki/Monte-Carlo_Masters" title="Monte-Carlo Masters">
        Monte-Carlo Masters
       </a>
       1000 can amass a total of 19,500 points before the ATP Finals and end the calendar year with a maximum of 21,000 points. Up to day, the maximum points achieved by any player is 16,950 by
       <a href="/wiki/Novak_Djokovic" title="Novak Djokovic">
        Novak Djokovic
       </a>
       , on June 6, 2016.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-13">
        <a href="#cite_note-13">
         [10]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <h2>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Ranking_method">
        Ranking method
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=ATP_Rankings&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Ranking method">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h2>
      <p>
       Since the introduction of the ATP rankings the method used to calculate a player's ranking points has changed several times.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-14">
        <a href="#cite_note-14">
         [11]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-15">
        <a href="#cite_note-15">
         [12]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <h3>
       <span id="Points_distribution_.282009_.E2.80.93_present.29">
       </span>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Points_distribution_(2009_–_present)">
        Points distribution (2009 – present)
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=ATP_Rankings&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Points distribution (2009 – present)">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>
       </span>
      </h3>
      <p>
       <i>
        Points are awarded as follows:

        <a href="#cite_note-17">
         [14]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>

      <ul>
       <li>
        (ATP 1000 series) Qualifying points changes to 12 points only if the main draw is larger than 56.
       </li>
       <li>
        (ATP 500 series) Qualifying points changes to 10 points only if the main draw is larger than 32
       </li>
       <li>
        (ATP 250 series) Qualifying points changes to 5 points only if the main draw is larger than 32
       </li>
       <li>
        Players who draw a bye in the first round in the ATP 1000 series and lose their first match in the second round are considered to have lost their first round and receive the points equivalent to first round loss. Similarly, loss in the second round of the ATP 500 series and the ATP 250 series after drawing bye in first round will result in 0 points being awarded.
        <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-18">
         <a href="#cite_note-18">
          [15]
         </a>
        </sup>
       </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
       In addition qualifiers and main draw entry players will then also receive the points in brackets for the rounds they reached.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-19">
        <a href="#cite_note-19">
         [16]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       Starting in 2016, points were no longer awarded for
       <a href="/wiki/Davis_Cup" title="Davis Cup">
        Davis Cup
       </a>
       ties,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-20">
        <a href="#cite_note-20">
         [17]
        </a>
       </sup>
       nor for the tennis tournament at the Summer Olympics.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-21">
        <a href="#cite_note-21">
         [18]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>

      <h2>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="No._1_ranked_players">
        No. 1 ranked players
       </span>
       <span class="mw-editsection">
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         [
        </span>
        <a href="/w/index.php?title=ATP_Rankings&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: No. 1 ranked players">
         edit
        </a>
        <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
         ]
        </span>

      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
       Main article:
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/List_of_ATP_number_1_ranked_singles_players" title="List of ATP number 1 ranked singles players">
        List of ATP number 1 ranked singles players
       </a>
      </div>

        </a>

       <h2>

        <span class="mw-headline" id="Players_with_highest_career_rank_2–5">
         Players with highest career rank 2–5
        </span>
        <span class="mw-editsection">
         <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
          [
         </span>
         <a href="/w/index.php?title=ATP_Rankings&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: Players with highest career rank 2–5">
          edit
         </a>
         <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
          ]
         </span>
        </span>
       </h2>
       <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
        See also:
        <a href="/wiki/Open_Era_tennis_records_%E2%80%93_men%27s_singles#ATP_Rankings_achievements" title="Open Era tennis records – men's singles">
         Open Era tennis records – men's singles § ATP Rankings achievements
        </a>
       </div>
       <p>
        The following is a list of players who were ranked world No.5 or higher but not No.1 in the period since the 1973 introduction of the
        <a href="/wiki/ATP_Tour" title="ATP Tour">
         ATP
        </a>
        computer rankings:
       </p>
       <ul>
        <li>
         Active players in
         <b>
          bold
         </b>
        </li>
       </ul>

        <span class="mw-headline" id="Notes">
         Notes
        </span>
        <span class="mw-editsection">
         <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
          [
         </span>

       </h2>
       <div class="reflist" style="list-style-type: lower-alpha;">
        <div class="mw-references-wrap">
         <ol class="references">
          <li id="cite_note-6">
           <span class="mw-cite-backlink">
            <b>
             <a href="#cite_ref-6">
              ^
             </a>
            </b>
           </span>
           <span class="reference-text">
            In weeks where there are not four Grand Slam tournaments and eight Masters 1000 tournaments in the ranking period, the number of a player's best results from all eligible tournaments in the ranking period will be adjusted accordingly.
           </span>
          </li>
          <li id="cite_note-8">
           <span class="mw-cite-backlink">
            <b>
             <a href="#cite_ref-8">
              ^
             </a>
            </b>
           </span>
           <span class="reference-text">
            At least one of these tournaments must follow the
            <a href="/wiki/US_Open_(tennis)" title="US Open (tennis)">
             US Open
            </a>
            .
           </span>
          </li>
          <li id="cite_note-11">
           <span class="mw-cite-backlink">
            <b>
             <a href="#cite_ref-11">
              ^
             </a>
            </b>
           </span>
           <span class="reference-text">
            "Accepted" means a direct acceptance, a qualifier, a special exempt, or a lucky loser, or having accepted a wild card.
           </span>

Here we access the correct table on wikipedia, that gives the ranking for men (I inspected the elements directly on the web page to find the right table and its beacons).

In [4]:
tables= soup.find_all('table',{"class":"wikitable nowrap"})
ATPsingleranks = tables[0]

Here we pull from that table the names, ranks and points for each player

In [5]:
ranks = []
points = []
players = []

#for table in ATPsingleranks:
rows = ATPsingleranks.find_all('tr')
    
for row in rows:
    cells = row.find_all('td')
        
    if len(cells) > 1:
        rank = cells[0]
        ranks.append(int(rank.text))
            
        player = cells[1]
        players.append(player.text.strip())
            
        point = cells[2]
        points.append((point.text.strip()))
            
            
df = pd.DataFrame(ranks, index= players, columns = ['Rank'])
df['ELO'] = points

df.head(10)

Here we had hashtags associated to each player, in order to look for them in tweets

In [6]:
twitternames=[]
for name in players:
    twitternames.append('#'+name.split('\xa0')[0].split(' ')[1].lower())
df['twitternames'] = twitternames

Connecting to twitter API and retrieving tweets¶

Here we have our consumer tokens (developper account of twitter):

In [66]:
consumer_key = ''
consumer_secret = ''
access_token = ''
access_token_secret = ''
In [67]:
# Authenticate
auth = tw.OAuthHandler(consumer_key, consumer_secret)
# Set Tokens
auth.set_access_token(access_token, access_token_secret)
# Instantiate API
api = tw.API(auth, wait_on_rate_limit=True)

Here we pull X tweets for each of the players, and put them in lists:

In [68]:
tweets = []
timestamps = []
for i in df.index:
    hashtag = (df['twitternames'][i])
    name = (df['index'][i])
    query = tw.Cursor(api.search
                      ,result_type = "recent" #values can be: popular, mixed, recent
                      #,until= "YYYY-MM-DD" #the API can only find tweets for the last week anyway.                    
                      , q=hashtag, lang='en').items(100)
    #Note that unpopular players (not top3) do not have 100 tweets last week, which might be a problem.
    #I need to find a way to get more tweets for each player, while having tweets that only correspond to one player.
    for tweet in query:
        tweets.append(tweet.text)
        timestamps.append(tweet.created_at)

Then, we put all the data in a dataframe (so the tweets will be easier to process with NLP)

In [70]:
loop = pd.DataFrame({'Tweet': tweets,
     'Timestamp': timestamps
    })
loop

Here we create flags, that indicate to whom each tweet relates:

In [71]:
def identify_subject(tweet, refs):
    flag = 0 
    for ref in refs:
        if tweet.find(ref) != -1:
            flag = 1
    return flag
In [72]:
for i in df.index:
    hashtag = (df['twitternames'][i])
    name = (df['index'][i])
    loop[name]=loop['Tweet'].apply(lambda x: identify_subject(x, hashtag))

Preprocessing with NLP¶

In [74]:
# Import stopwords
import nltk
from nltk.corpus import stopwords
# Import textblob
from textblob import Word, TextBlob
In [75]:
nltk.download('stopwords')
nltk.download('wordnet')
stop_words = stopwords.words('english')
player_names = df['index'].values.tolist()
custom_stopwords = ['RT']

[nltk_data] Downloading package wordnet to
[nltk_data]     C:\Users\louis\AppData\Roaming\nltk_data...
[nltk_data]   Package wordnet is already up-to-date!

Here we clean the tweets, remove what is unnecessary:

In [76]:
def preprocess_tweets(tweet, custom_stopwords):
    processed_tweet = tweet
    processed_tweet.replace('[^\w\s]', '')
    processed_tweet = " ".join(word for word in processed_tweet.split() if word not in player_names)
    processed_tweet = " ".join(word for word in processed_tweet.split() if word not in stop_words)
    processed_tweet = " ".join(word for word in processed_tweet.split() if word not in custom_stopwords)
    processed_tweet = " ".join(Word(word).lemmatize() for word in processed_tweet.split())
    return(processed_tweet)

loop['Processed Tweet'] = loop['Tweet'].apply(lambda x: preprocess_tweets(x, custom_stopwords))
loop.head()

Calculating sentiment with NLP¶

We will calculate polarity and subjectivity, however, only polarity interests us for the plots.

In [77]:
# Calculate polarity
loop['polarity'] = loop['Processed Tweet'].apply(lambda x: TextBlob(x).sentiment[0])
loop['subjectivity'] = loop['Processed Tweet'].apply(lambda x: TextBlob(x).sentiment[1])
loop.head()

Here we have some stats about each player's sentiment:

In [78]:
for i in df.index:
    name = (df['index'][i])
    a = loop[loop[name]==1][[name, 'polarity', 'subjectivity']].groupby(name).agg([np.mean, 'count'])
    print(a)

Visualisation¶

Plotting the rolling moving averages for each player:

In [79]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
fig, axes = plt.subplots(10, 1, figsize=(10, 40))
c=0
for i in df.index:
    name = (df['index'][i])
    rolling = loop[loop[name]==1][['Timestamp', 'polarity']]
    rolling = rolling.sort_values(by='Timestamp', ascending=True)
    rolling['MA Polarity']=rolling.polarity.rolling(10, min_periods=3).mean()
    axes[c].plot(rolling['Timestamp'], rolling['MA Polarity'])
    axes[c].set_title("\n".join([name+" 's Polarity"]))
    c=c+1
fig.suptitle("\n".join(["Top 10 tennnis players sentiment analysis"]), y=0.98)

plt.show()
